\subsection*{Modern random number generators}

\begin{itemize}
\item Key idea: use a complex function to generate next item
\item Cool fact: division is a pretty complex function!  That is what
is used in most random number generators
\item Personal favorite: functions $f(x)$ that are so complex that
$f^{-1}(y)$ can't be computed.  Sometimes used in strong random number
generators.  (Hint: simulate it backwards!)
\end{itemize}

\section*{Problem statement}

How to count stuff?
\begin{itemize}
\item Two problems,
\begin{itemize}
\item what to count?  Interesting and difficult.
\item How to count it? tricks and fancy mathematics.
\end{itemize}
\item Key idea discovered by Gretchen Weikert
\begin{itemize}
\item Perry preschool project was run by David Weikert (1970's)
\item Tested the idea of planning as an important educational
activity: Motto: ``Plan, do, review.''
\item Video of his daughter discovering our trick:
\begin{itemize}
\item 8 rows of 12 items
\item teacher asks how many there are?
\item Gretchen says, we could count them?
\item Teacher asks for a better plan?
\item Gretchen thinks, says, we could write down 12 a total of 8 time
and add them up.
\item And hence multiplication was discovered.
\end{itemize}
\item Still the best (i.e. only) controlled experiment in education!
\end{itemize}
\item We will use the same answer as Gretchen
